You slide the filing cabinet open and prepare to do a little snooping.
It contains the Brandt file, the Finch file, the Grislewood file, the LeBlanc file, the Marx file, the McBride file, the Minsky file, the Potts file, the Sotherby file and the Yoshida file.
> read brandt

> read brandt
Traudel Brandt gets wildly uneven grades, often aceing a subject one semester only to fail miserably the next, or vice versa.   Her student evaluations are scathing - the Headmistress has written that she's a "lunatic beatnik" who's "likely to perish of a social disease."   She's been written up several times for insubordination, though you rarely remember her being particularly rude.  It's more that she distains -- and is amused by -- everyone equally.

Her parents are German communists who fled the Nazis but have never attempted to gain U.S. citizenship, and refuse to speak anything but German unless absolutely necessary (something that's infuriated Hannigan to no end in dealing with them, along with their politics and their unmarried status).    Traudel had been arrested multiple times for bizarre reasons (including flying down the street naked, serial arson involving scarecrows, and sending coded "threats" to government officials which turned out to be erotic poetry and fragmented quotes from radio quiz shows.)   She's been passed from psychiatrist to psychiatrist, leaving a paper trail of disgusted professional opinions to the effect that she was perfectly sane and simply looking for attention.

Two years ago, she decided to have a baby just to see what it was like.  Her son Nuklear-Reactor Brandt currently lives with his grandparents.
> read finch

> read finch
Renee Finch gets excellent grades, though the Headmistress complains about her "dreamy" nature and states "if she doesn't take her nose out of a book once in a while, she's going to get it stuck there."   A number of the files are citations for academic excellence.  You also find a clipping of a short story from Amazing Tales magazine -- "A Year On Venus", written by "R. Swan".   It's a little like a science fiction version of Robinson Crusoe.

You were hoping to find some juicy secrets about your quiet roommate, but she seems to have led a pretty unremarkable life so far.   The most exciting incident is detailed in a series of clippings from a Mississippi newspaper -- her parents were run out of town and nearly killed after it was discovered that her mother was using glamour and memory spells on most of the community in order to evade anti-miscegenation laws.  Disavowed by both families, they fled to the west coast with their infant daughter to start a new life.  Kind of funny that the fruit of such a torridly romantic story should be a mousy little spud like Renee.
> read grislewood

> read grislewood
Most of the files on "the Grizz" are very boring.  There's a copy of her resume, a certificate from Black Forest Culinary Academy, and a lot of old payroll slips and insurance forms.  There's also a neatly typed employee evaluation which states that she's an enthusiastic worker,  but shows some warning signs of heritary dementia which "bear due consideration."

At the back of the file is a request for salary increase.  The reason given is "if I'm gonna be expected to do Frank and Petunia's jobs now I ought to get more than a slop jockey's pay."   The sheet of paper appears to have been crumpled up and then smoothed out again.
> read leblanc

> read leblanc
You begin reading your own secret file.   Most of it is the sort of low-level not-very-complimentary stuff you could have guessed -- "frequently tardy", "lack of effort", that sort of thing.  It's kind of disheartening.  You always thought maybe the reason she was so hard on you was that she had a secret soft spot for you and was striving to maintain a professional distance, or that maybe she thought you had potential and wanted to push you to be more than what you were.  It turns out she just really didn't like you very much.
> read marx

> read marx
Gwendolyn Marx has sky-high grades, which is probably the only reason she hasn't been kicked out of Whitefield.   Her file contains nearly a full ream of paper detailing the many, many rules she's broken.  She was involved in most of your own violations and plenty of solo endeavors, including a number of them even you hadn't heard about.   Most recently, she was arrested for stealing a car in July, but was let off with a week of community service when she was able to turn a sheep into a functional replacement (a feat normally considered to be PhD-level work).

The final entry is a note written in the Headmistress' crabbed hand.   "The Marx girl is still going nowhere.   Caught her this morning destroying part of the lawn in a scuffle with McBride.   She'd enchanted one of her socks to function as a reusable concussive grenade that was powerful enough to shatter stone.   I confiscated it, of course, and told her how disappointed I was in her--as if that will make a difference to her sort.   All those brains and she can think of nothing else to do with them.  It's no wonder things have come to this sorry state."
> read mcbride

> read mcbride
Tallulah McBride's grades are quite bad.  According to this, she's been bouncing from school to school all around the world, frequently missing large chunks of classes in order to go on big game hunts with her mother.  You remember her missing almost a month of class last year to chase off after an African reticulated sphinx.   There's a note from her stepfather begging the school to keep her on because "no English witching school will take her" and promising to pay for renovations to the tune of several thousand dollars if she's allowed to remain.

She was born in England and lived there until the age of ten.  Since then, she's attended schools in Germany, Zimbabwe, Australia and Brazil.  Before enrolling at Whitefield, she attended a coeducational school for normals in New York, but was yanked out mid-term after a pregnancy scare.
> read minsky

> read minsky
Mary Jane Minsky's grades are aggressively so-so, with the exception of her mathemagic grades, which are even worse than yours.   Hannigan doesn't seem to have much to say about her, except to note, rather curtly, that she doesn't cause any discipline problems and is probably doing as well as she can.   Her sole non-grade source of demerits was the time she and Jenny were caught at a drive-in on the mainland after curfew.   You get the feeling that the headmistress doesn't really like her but can't rationally explain why.  Sometimes you feel that way too.

Half the file is taken up with the sugary inspirational poetry MJ is always penning, mimeographing, and handing out to everyone.  Every page of it is worse than the last.  There's also a notice certifying her as the official Whitefield Witching Academy 1956 Prom Queen and a newpaper clipping which states she was Miss Boise Junior Potato Queen of 1954.
> read potts

> read potts
The thick sheaf of paper contains almost forty years of records from the employment of Franklin Potts, a gardener and maintenance man.  You don't remember much about Frank, only that he was rather gruff and that he left sometime last year.  According to the files, he was rewarded with early retirement for a lifetime of "tremendous effort, especially in consideration of his normalcy".   His salary on the last few pay records is circled in red.

In the back of the folder is a very sincere letter from Jenny Yoshida begging for Frank to be kept on.
> read sotherby

> read sotherby
Miss Sotherby didn't generate many records in the brief period she worked as a maid at Whitefield; she'd only been here for about a year, replacing the ancient Mrs. Stoltz.   She was written up several times for laziness and insubordination, every instance of which she furiously contested, and was formally given notice in May that she was not welcome to return in the fall.  No one has yet been hired to replace her.
> read yoshida

> read yoshida
Jenny Yoshida's grades are above average, but not great.  There's a carbon copy of a personal note the headmistress sent, thanking her for a delicious apple pie.  In her private evaluation, she writes that Jenny spends entirely too much time with plants and not enough with people, which "could affect her growth in the future."   Jenny's only demerits are for being out after curfew and a tantilizing writeup for "lewd conduct" that unfortunately doesn't go into further detail.

Her personal history notes that her family was placed in an internment camp when she was three and that her father died in a drunk-driving accident five years ago, neither of which you knew before today.  She almost never talks about anything related to her family.
