> read trashy

> read trashy
"But sir!  Would you unwoman me?" I said, fluttering my fan.  The room was quite humid, and I must confess the ministrations of Lord Barthby the Younger made it more humid still.

"Nay, my good Lady Tottingbow," said that good gentleman, working avidly at the underpinning of my unmentionables, "it is indeed your very womanhood which I most value in you."

"And you your manhood!" I rejoindered, just as his efforts yielded ripe and voluptuous fruit.  For scarce my words had left my lips than, in a great cloudburst of ripping fabric,  my heaving bosom burst through layers of taffeta and whalebone to heave freely at long last.  It hove, and hove, until I was near prostrate from the very heaving of it.

"Oh, Tottingbow!  Tottingbow!" he cried huskily.

"Oh, the Younger!  The Younger!" I shrieked in ecstasy.

Our lips crushed together like bales of writhing velvet as his powerful hands rent at my overflowing pulchritude.   Suddenly, the bedchamber door was flung open!  Framed it in stood the sweat-slick figure of Eduardo, the gardener's boy.  Could it be?  Had he discovered it was not my invalid twin sister, but me, with whom he had of late spent more than one afternoon twined in decadent panoply?  For his exquisite face split like some mad glorious sculpture into a devil's grin of triumph, and, tool upraised, he rushed towards the bed!
