> read textbook

> read textbook
The book contains a number of recipes.   Some that catch your eye include:

Spellbase --  It's not hard to see why this specially prepared medium has all but replaced water as the prime ingredient in potions since the previous edition.   Inactive on its own but capable of "storing" many of the most popular effects, spellbase is colorless and tasteless (in fact, using spellbase, you can add non-magical flavoring to your potions with no ill effects -- no more choking down spicy shots of Pyroblaze straight!)    Unless you're a real diehard do-it-yourselfer, we recommended purchasing spellbase rather than making it your own; the expense is worth it, as store-bought base is extremely stable and partially consumed potions can be re-spelled and re-used.

Temporal Oil -- This coating dissolves and negates the effect of a temporal locking spell, restoring objects and persons frozen in time.
A talented alchemist must add the following to a spellbase preparation: A hunk of silver, a chunk of gold, a helping of rye bread and the bough of a plant which does not exist.

Boil the mixture at the highest temperature possible, then allow to cool and use on affected areas.
> x set

> x set
A complicated array of crystal decanters, aluminum fixtures, and plastic tubing.   A talented alchemist could make all kinds of things with this.
