A Familiar Room
This is the room where you live with your roommate, Renee.  It's a little ridiculous that you don't get your own room when there are so few students, but Hannigan says it "builds character".   Anyway, you have to admit that while you would have preferred Gwen, Renee's probably the second-best person you could have gotten.   She's neat, but not so neat that she gets on your case when you're not, and quiet, but doesn't complain when you make noise.   The only irritating thing she does is leave stacks of her novels and comics everywhere.  She took most of them home, but there are still plenty scattered around her side of the the room--you own side looks pretty bare by comparison.
You can go east.
You can see a fantasy paperback and lurid four color trash.
> x fantasy

> x fantasy
A fantasy paperback entitled "The Jewel of Zorath".  The cover shows a shirtless blonde barbarian splitting a skeleton's skull with his axe.   You borrowed it from the library last year and never got around to returning it.
> read it

> read it
"By Mfrik!" roared Targos, swinging his pitted bastard sword toward the smoldering neck of the serpentine dragon.  "You shall scourge Porgrathia no more!"

The black, ebon blade deeply sliced the foul beast's sinewy hide, coating the roiling barbarian in steaming gouts of pestilent ichor.   Targos snarled disdainfully as the grotesque head bounced lithely across the shattered flagstones of the granite floor.   The wench G'morlamissa wrinkled her opaque nose and grimaced her displeasure, folding her supple arms across her bounteous, leather-clad orbs in a gesture of impatience.

"Now may we go?" she asked.   "Truly, the warriors of Amazaria would have taken but a minute -- nay, half a moment -- to accomplish such a simple task."

"Amazaria!  Bah!" roared Targos.  "A Porgrathian fighting man could face half a hundred of those ill-trained wenches and triumph!"

G'morlamissa sneered.  "Any one of my sisters could thrash a score of your loutish whelpings before breakfast and another twoscore after!"

An incandescent hiss interrupted the duel of wits.  For the dread wyrm Val'skag'ska'thramos was rising anew--two loathesome countenances sprouting from its still-ichorous neck.

"It seems fate has presented us with the opportunity to settle our wager," the wench said, a grim smirk twisting her fair features.   "Shall we, then?"

Targos roared his assent, and swung.
