> ask automat about pluto

> ask automat about pluto
"Right away."  A ripple passes through the piles of books, and your selection materializes in your hands.
> read sci-fi

> read sci-fi
They say a good book can take you places, but this one is a little more literal than most.  As soon as you open it, the room is bathed in an eerie blue light.  Tendrils of plasma play along the edge of the pages as the words swirl and a circular portal appears, hovering over the floor.  You feel yourself being helplessly drawn into it...

And land with a jolt on hard-packed soil.  You struggle to your feet, scooping up the book (which is still faintly glowing) and look around at the alien world in which you've landed.   Reddish-brown trees draped with drooping tentacles like Spanish moss and tufts of fluffy orange flowers, each of which follows you with a single beady black eye in the center.  You've landed on Pluto, or at least the version of it depicted in the book!

You're surrounded by tractless steamforest in all directions, and can see nothing around you but the creepy trees and the burnished golden sky hanging above you like a chandelier.   Behind you, a stabilized portal leads to the library.

Plutovian Jungle
This sweltering red-and-brown forest of tentacles and twisted, slithery trees is like nothing you've ever seen in the real world.    Insects of all kinds tweet and yammer from the underbrush.   The only signs of human life are a set of bootprints in the thick dust, leading north.  There's a portal to the south through which a library is visible.
You can go north or south.
You can see tentacle trees.
> x trees

> x trees
Slimy tentacles hang lazily from the branches like gobbets of drool, swaying slightly despite the utter lack of wind.
> n

> n
You pick your way through the forest, stumbling over underbrush, until you find yourself at the bank of a shallow stream the color of blood.  Across the water, you see a campsite in which two human astronauts, dressed in skin-tight, shiny uniforms, are trying to get a fire going.   You recognize one as Jack Rocket, that lantern-jawed space adventurer guy that Renee is not-so-secretly gaga over.    The other is Renee herself!

The two glance up from the embers, spotting you.   Renee's eyes widen in surprise.  "Page!  What are you--"

"Get down, Stella!" Jack Rocket cries, shoving her to the sandy ground.  "I KNEW we hadn't seen the last of her!"

Smoothly, he draws a goofy-looking ray gun from the holster at his hip and points it at you.   "Hands up, NATASHA!"

"That's not Natasha!" Renee protests.  "She's from my class!"

"Nonsense!  What would one of your Academy chums be doing out here?"  Jack says, holding the gun steady.  "There's only one other person on this planet, and that's Natasha Ivanov, the dirty red infiltrator who boarded our ship, the Atomic Yank, in the guise of our science officer, only to sabotage it, stranding us here on Pluto!   Back to finish us off, eh, you Commie rat?"

You protest, but you barely get a word in before Jack's finger twitches.  A beam of sizzling emerald light misses your face by inches, and you hear the sound of splintering wood behind you, followed by the thud of a tree trunk slamming into the ground.

"I won't have you filling my impressionable young ward's tender ears with your propaganda!" he barks.

"I'm telling you, that isn't Natasha!" Renee says helplessly.  "She doesn't even look like her!   Her name is Page LeBlanc, she's my roommate at--ah, back on Earth.  She...she's probably here for... a rescue mission!"

Jack shakes his head.  "The ScanTron would have told us if another ship had landed.  No, my beloved ward, I'm afraid your yearning for home has driven you to Plutovian Jungle Dementia!  Return to the ship at once!  I'll hold off this blood-crazed Bolshevik!"

"But--"

"Go!"

Renee shrugs helplessly at you as Jack drives her westward, shielding her with his body as he keeps the ray gun pointed right between your eyes.   You stay still, broiling with heat and feeling your heart pound out of your chest, until you're sure you're alone in the campsite.

Earthbase Three Sigma
You are in a hastily abandoned campsite on the sandy bank of a shallow stream.   To the west, the land rises precipitously.   A very faint path leads south into the jungle.  All other directions are impassably overgrown.
You can go south or west.
