> x sarcophagus
A large stone sarcophagus, its lid cracked down the middle from the impact with the floor.
> open it

> open it
You open it.
It contains a coffin.
> x coffin

> x coffin
A large pine coffin wrapped in chains, which are locked tight with about twenty different locks.  Combination locks.  Padlocks.  Puzzle boxes.  Chinese finger traps.   Ancient rusty lumps of irons.  Modern electronic locks.  Pretty much any kind of lock you can imagine, it's on there.
> yeggle it

> yeggle it
Every one of the locks drops off like a ripe apple, followed by the lid.  It's good to be a witch!
> x mummy

> x mummy
It appears to be a girl wrapped in golden foil like a mummy.    You can't make out facial features, but by the process of elimination and what you know of your classmate's heights and body types, it's probably Traudel Brandt.    Or a life-sized chocolate sculpture of her.   You'll have to UNWRAP it to find out for sure.
> unwrap mummy

> unwrap mummy
You peel back the foil, hoping that the girl inside is alive.   When you've removed enough to see the pale features of Traudel Brandt, you amend your hopes: now you hope that she's alive, and that she isn't naked under there.   You wouldn't put it past her to wrap herself nude in foil and bury herself at sea.  You wouldn't really put it past Traudel to do ANYthing.

The good news is, she's alive.

Her eyes blink open.  "Oh.  Rescued already?  Zat certainly didn't take long.  Vas expectink to be down zere for fifty years, minimum, completely sessile like sea sponge, vith only thoughts to keep company until discovered by divers of the deep sea, yes?"

You start to explain the situation, but she waves you away.  "Yes, yes, you're mein hero.  Well, I had planned to spend afternoon goink mad but it appears zat's off ze agenda zo perhaps I'll get in a little smokink instead.   Ja!"

She tears off the last of the foil, drops a wadded-up ball of gold leaf about six inches in diameter at her feet, and wanders off.

