Your policy of glutting yourself on everything you can get your hands on has served you in good stead.   The scent of gingerbread tickles your nostrils as you pass through the portal, but you have no desire to stop and eat.

Dining Hall
You continue on into the dining hall--or what used to be the dining hall, anyway.  The tables have been pushed to the sides of the room, allowing the bare white floor to gleam in the the guttering light of a few medieval-looking lanterns which have been placed on red-and-white striped poles--candy canes, that is.  You take another step, feel something squish under your shoes, and look to down to see that you're leaving footprints in the...snow?  No, upon closer examination, it's frosting.   The sweet smell of it tickles at your nostrils. It's a good thing you're so full, because you're standing smack in the middle of what must be billions of calories worth of sugary sludge.

On the south end of the hall, you can see what looks like a miniature forest.  The light of more lanterns shines through heavily frosted pine boughs.
You can go north or south.
> s

> s
You slog south through ever-thicker icing.

Frosted Forest
You've entered a forest of pines the size of a typical Christmas tree, each covered in thick dollops of white frosting and dusted with green sugar crystals.  It's  quite dark here.  If you couldn't just make out the ceiling tiles by squinting, you'd have a hard time telling you weren't outside.
Further south, you can spot the  flickering light fire reflecting off of the polished steel of the lunch counter.  An inviting yellow-orange glow emanates from the kitchen, bathing the "snow" in homey hues right out of a painting.
You can go north or south.
> s

> s
You slog south when you feel something suddenly tighten around your leg.  Before you can react, your feet and yanked out from under you and you find yourself hanging upside-down from the dining hall ceiling, caught in a snare.

"Bagged another one!" cackles a voice gleefully.  Moments later, a burly old woman bursts out of the kitchen and makes her way over to her, displaying a yellowed grin full of overly-large teeth.  You recognize her as Baba Grislewood, the school cook, but something's different about her now.  Her eyes sparkle with barely restrained madness.

She clucks her tongue at the sight of you.  "Scrawny little runt," she says, shaking her head.  "Barely any meat on her.  Well, no matter!  Granny's gingerbread will soon have you fattened up nice and plump!"

She cuts you down.  Her arms feel as though they were banded with iron, and you're so dizzy you barely know where you are, anyway.
Grislewood bends the bars of the cage, forces you inside, and bends them back into place.  "I'll be back with din-din, dearie!" she laughs as she turns and stomps away.

"Pmmph?" someone says behind you.

You turn.  You recognize the blonde hair and blue eyes of Mary Jane Minsky, an annoyingly chipper girl you were hoping to see as little as possible of this year.  Instead you're actually seeing more of her--quite a bit more.  Since the last time you laid eyes on her, she must have gained fifty pounds.

She blushes and swallows the mouthful of gingerbread.  "I know, I know.   But just wait until you try her gingerbread -- it's to die for!  I can't stop eating the stuff!  It's almost worth turning into a butterball."  Her glossy pink lips turn down in a moue.  "Except there's just one teeny-tiny problem, and that's that I'm pretty sure she's gonna eat me once I'm fat enough."

Mary Jane pulls another gingerbread man from the basket she's holding and nibbles on it as she talks.  "See, she's being acting awful kooky ever since the welcome party--well, everyone has, really.  Except me and Jenny.  We think it has something to do with the punch they drank.   I didn't have any because I'm..." She grins sheepishly.  "...on a diet.  But everyone else just went nuttier than a Cinncinnati fruitcake!   The Grizz started thinking she was her great-grandmother from back in the Old Country or wherever.  At first we managed to get away and put up a barricade, but then Jenny started feeling sick.  She said she needed something in her greenhouse and she'd only be five minutes, but she never came back!   So I went looking for her, and that's when the Grizz got me."

You explain about Jenny, and Mary Jane's eyes light up.  "Wowsers!  That's great!   I can't wait to tell her what happened to me!  Except I guess we gotta get outta here without getting eaten, first, huh?"  She looks thoughtful.  "Y'know, she's pretty focused on her work.  I bet you could squeeze out through the bars and get the drop on her!   I'd have done it but, uh... I don't think I'd fit."   She pats her stomach ruefully.
Grislewood bends the bars of the cage, forces you inside, and bends them back into place.  "I'll be back with din-din, dearie!" she laughs as she turns and stomps away.

"Pmmph?" someone says behind you.

