Grislewood Kitchen
This is a large institutional kitchen haphazardly converted into a witch's laboratory.   The sinks have been converted into makeshift cauldrons, and yellow candles are dribbling wax everywhere.       The doors to the north have been blocked by several large slabs of stale gingerbread, and the only other direction you can go -- besides back into the cage -- is south, into the walk-in freezer.

Baba Grislewood is here, working at her cauldrons and seeming remarkably unconcerned that you're wandering around out of your cage.

A cage big enough to hold at least two people is plopped down in the middle of the kitchen.   Mary Jane Minsky is clutching at the bars nervously, silently pleading with you to get rid of Grislewood and save her.

You can go in, north or south.
You can see Baba Grislewood.
> put pills in jack

> put pills in jack
Done.
> give jack to baba

> give jack to baba
She squints to make out the object you're holding.  "Oh my!  A human head!  I knew I had one or two lying around.   Into the stew with you!"   She hefts the jack o' lantern overhead and drops it theatrically into the sink.
SPLOOOSH!  The orange globe sinks into the liquid, its megadose of pills fizzing and disintegrating in the water.   "Yes, yes, there we go," Baba Grizzlewood says.  "Now, let's see here..."

She ladles up some broth and takes a sip.  "Hmm...(sip)...not bad...(sip)...a little pumpkinny....(sip)....pumpky...pumpkininny...(sip)...

The oddest look comes over her face.   The cloudiness in her eyes begins to clear, and she looks at you with sudden acuity.

"Page?  Is that you?"

"Where are we?" she continues, blinking.  "What...happened to my kitchen?  Why am I boiling a pumpkin in the sink?  It's not Friday."

"Maybe tell her to let me out of the cage?" Mary Jane hints.

"The cage," Mrs. Grislewood mutters.  "The cage.  The cage.  Of course."   She waves her wand absently, and the bars of the cage go limp and rubbery.   "Oh my...did my wand always leave these...sparkly trails?"

"Yay!" Mary Jane squeals, squeezing between the stretchy bars and grabbing you in a squishy bear hug.  "You totally saved my bacon, Page!  I would have been eaten up for sure!"

Mrs. Grislewood has become distracted by her own wand.    Casually punching the stale gingerbread slab in two as if it were made of Styrofoam, she wanders out of the kitchen, waving the stick of wood like a metronome.  "Oooh.  Lovely."

Mary Jane shrugs.  "I guess she'll be all right."   She eyes one of the lumps of rye gingerbread, which has broken off from the main mass and rolled across the floor to your feet.    "I don't know about you," she laughs, following the Grizz out the door, "but I don't think I'll be hungry for gingerbread for a looooooong time!"
