Rotunda
You are in the central rotunda of the school, just under the turquoise dome.  A beautiful mural adorns the circular ceiling, but the rest of the room looks like a junk heap.  Tables are overturned, puddles of punch are splattered across the floor, and loose balloons bob listlessly around the upper reaches.

The foyer and the exit lie to the west.  To the north are the administrative offices, and to the south, where the dining hall used to be, is a curious round portal made of gingerbread.    A grand staircase leads up the second floor of the rotunda.
You can go west, north, south, east or up.
You can see a punchbowl, a welcome banner, Gwendolyn Marx and puddles.
> use oil on Gwen

> use oil on Gwen
You pour the oil out over Gwen's head.  As the greasy liquid soaks into her hair and clothes, you begin to see movement.  Slow as molasses, you see her finish swallowing the liquid and lower the cup.  Her eyes drift to your face.

"Paaaaaaaaaaaageeee?" she says in baritone surprise, even now speeding up.  "Whaaat aaaare yooou dooing here?"

She takes in the destroyed rotunda, then looks back down at her paper cup.   "Or maybe I should be asking: who spiked the punch?"

You explain what's going on, hoping that this is the last time.  You're getting a little tired of telling people the same story over and over.  Gwen listens.

"Sounds like someone really had it in for this place," she says thoughtfully.   "Have you found Hannigan yet?  She's the only one unaccounted for, and as fond as I'm not of the old bat, we probably shouldn't just leave her if she's been transformed into a lamp or something.   See if you can dig her up, and bring her to me if you do.   In the meantime I'll just hang out here.  I don't want to spoil this new 'doing all the work yourself' kick you're on."

> give monkey to Gwen

> give monkey to Gwen
"That looks like her, all right.  And you found it in her office?"  Gwen brings her wand close to the toy and winces.  "This thing is practically glowing.  It's gotta be her."

She sets the monkey down and makes a few passes over it, mumbling spells that are way beyond anything you can understand.  You shrink back a little.  If there's one strain on your friendship--not that Gwen ever seems to notice--it's that without even trying, she's so far ahead of you you sometimes feel like a helpless child by comparison.

Gwen raises her wand.  "Down to the last spell.  Here we go!"

There's an explosion of crackling purple light.
...and the monkey is slightly singed, but otherwise unchanged.

Gwen frowns.   "Oooo-kay.  Looks like it's not her."  She bites her lip.  "But someone went to a lot of trouble to make it look like the headmistress was caught in the same spell that got the rest of us.  Someone who knew enough about all of us to set all this up... Page, I think I know where you've got to go."

You've never seen Gwen take her glasses off before, not even in the shower, but she takes them off now and gently places them on you.
"Truesight enchantment," she explains.  "It lets you, uh, see the truth, get it?  And if my suspicions are correct, you might want to start looking for the truth in Hannigan's office.  Just be ready for what you might find, okay?   Don't want to sound like a wet blanket or anything, but it might be dangerous."

You protest.  Isn't she going to help you?

"Nah.   You've got this one.  You handled everything, right?  You're tougher than you think you are, Page.  Besides," she grins, "I'm just too lazy!"
