> give Hannigan file to Henrietta
She takes the files, frowning.  "What's this?"

She reads it, at first glancing up at you after every sentence to make sure you don't try anything, but then growing more and more absorbed.

"This... this says..." She gulps.  "This is from that doctor I talked to."

She looks at you, puzzled.

"This says that I should be in that special school.  It says I can catch up to the other kids."  Henrietta shakes her head sadly.   "Grandma said the doctors just thought I was stupid and I could show that they were wrong by working hard, but that's not what it says here.   I know she wants what's best for me.  But... she lied."

She sniffles.  "And it's not just about that.  She promised she wasn't going to hurt anyone, but--but I can still read!  I know what that potion she was making did.  I just...I didn't want to believe it."

She looks away.

"I guess...I guess you need to stop her," she said.  "Just please don't hurt her if you can help it.  She's still my grandma!"
> e

> e
You step out onto the beach, the early evening sun throwing your shadow across the pebbley sand.  Down by the waterline, you spot a large maroon Packard, the same one you've seen the Headmistress flying over the island in.

You hear a slam and the click of a lock, and here comes the Headmistress around the side of the car.  She stops when she sees you.

"Miss LeBlanc," she says icily.  "Tardy as usual, I see.  If you laid one hand on my granddaughter--"

You raise your wand and she waves a hand lazily, throwing you back into the sand.   "You will listen to what I have to say."
"For years I've been watching this institution die a slow death.    This used to be a school for real witches.  The best of the best.  I was tenth in my class--tenth!--and I was damned proud of that.  Back then, that was an achievement.   Then standards slipped, and kept slipping.  Decent people pulled their daughters out, and in order to survive the administration had to open the doors to others.  Then they came to me.  'Whip them into shape', they said.   As if one could whip what is already decayed.   And look at what things have come to.  Look at what all our grand tradition has come down to.  Unrepentant hoodlums like you and Marx.  Moral degenerates.  Arrogant thugs.  Not a one of them with any concern for what it means to be a proper witch.  The school might as well have been empty."

She smiles grimly.

"So I thought--why shouldn't it be?"
"There are plenty of dark witches still running around.  Why shouldn't one have attacked a school full of defenseless students?   It was chaos.  The survivors will back me up.  And that includes you, Miss LeBlanc; oh, I had a special punishment for you, like the others, but since you couldn't be bothered to show up I'll just overwrite your mind.   A bit messy, rather hard on the brain cells, but it's not as if you ever use them anyway."

She draws herself up.  "So, final exam time, Miss LeBlanc.  Let's see if you have any capacity at all to take things seriously.  We are going to fight a duel, you and I, and as I dislike using violence on my students I shall take an entirely defensive tack.  When you fail to land a blow on me, I shall take that as a tacit admission of inferiority, and I shall expect you to submit to the procedure like the decent young lady you never have been."

She swirls her wand, surrounding herself with an undulating shield of dark water.  "Take your best shot!"

